<i>Posted by lPLAZl on 09-27-2003 09:37 PM:</i>

<p><b> </b></p>

<p>Light refraction?  <br />
<br />
Since CuSo4:5H20 is naturally blue, and because I see a 5water in the formula, my guess is that when you burn it, it loses some of its mass due to the water evaporation - which is why it turns white (loses the pentahydrate?).  When dissolved or hydrated back in water, it would just get the 5water back and revert to the original color...<br />
<br />
That's my guess after looking at some old chem notes, take it as you will.<!-- BEGIN TEMPLATE: postbit_signature -->
