<i>Posted by kanludar on 09-28-2003 02:41 AM:</i>

<p><b> </b></p>

<p>Yes it does turn blue (its orginal color) after being heated which turns it white/gray.  However, I am posed with the question why does it turn blue again after being rehydrated.  My best guess<br />
<br />
If blue CuSO45H2O is heated strongly, the hydration water is driven off, and what is left is a white powdery CuSO4 (anhydrous copper(II) sulfate). The blue will reappear if the copper sulfate is exposed to even small amounts of moisture.<br />
<br />
The water-copper ion complex absorbs photons of yellow or red light. This absorption of a photon promotes an electron from the water to the copper(II) ion. Since only yellow or red light is absorbed, blue light is transmitted, and the crystals appear blue.</p>

<!-- END TEMPLATE: printthreadbit --><!-- BEGIN TEMPLATE: printthreadbit -->
